<BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>From what my friends level 57 wizard can do with the inate crits 1 spell in 30 seems to hit for double damage.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>I hate to beat you over the head with this again, but innate crits aren't <I>capable</I> of double damage. They are on a sliding scale, maxing at about +66%. Assuming linear distribution (which seems like an accurate assumption from my experience) that makes the average innate crit +33%. Even if our crit rate was 1:30 as you suggest (any evidence to support that btw?) it would still barely represent a 1% power shift for wizards.<P>No matter how you try to downplay the numbers, they don't lie: innate crits are only decoration. You know it. Sometimes you admit it, but then you go back to your old tune. You remember when you were saying that innate crits would singlehandedly make wizards more damaging than anybody else in the game? You know that oppinion is utter BS, and yet you've never retracted it and you keep falling back on it. You won't let go of it. WHY?<P>Nobody can take you seriously, when you refuse to let go of obvious falsehoods.<P>Just let go of it man.<P><BR>Now...<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>The fact that Wizards can display decent damage though inate crits from level 11 and above will provide the player population with the preceptive evidence required to establish them again as "damage dealers" in EQ "society". There is no such evidence for Magicians. <HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>This is a legitimate gripe, but you're wrong. Pet damage is visible.<P>If you still want more visible damage, maybe you should consider asking for <I>pet</I> crits, if you don't already have them. That would make sense, as it would serve to distinguish mages as the master pet class, the same way innate crits help to distinguish wizards as the master DD class.<P>--------------------<P>Setch<BR>54th level drow wizard,<BR>baron of Lucid Chimera<BR>Vazaelle server
